      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks, i checked the html and the image is definitely inside its own div. i tried adding that margin-bottom to the container like you said but it barely moved anything. the text still feels like it's being squashed under the image on my iphone. \n\nis there something else in the layout logic or maybe the flex settings that could be causing this? it feels like the elements aren't respecting the vertical flow at all.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The issue might not be with the flex container alone. Adjusting the `margin-bottom` alone can sometimes be insufficient, especially when flex items are involved. Return to the flex settings, and make sure the stacking context is appropriately managed so that the header maintains its intended spacing over the product image:\n\n```css\n.product__info-container {\n  display: flex;\n  flex-direction: column;\n  padding: 20px;\n  align-items: flex-start; /* Align children to the start of the flex container */\n}\n\n@media screen and (max-width: 749px) {\n  .product__info-container {\n    padding: 10px;\n  }\n  .product__image-container {\n    max-width: 100%;\n    margin-bottom: 15px; /* Try increasing this or add other styles for centering */\n  }\n  .product__title {\n    font-size: 1.8rem;\n  }\n  .product__description {\n    margin-top: 15px;\n  }\n}\n```\n\nPlease examine if the `align-items` property is correctly influencing the vertical alignment of your child elements. If your header is distinct from the title and price, consider applying the adjustments specifically to that header. Adjust the overall height",
      "source": "target",
